    The root cause of the crash — "Deallocation of freed memory" — is a         
    double-free error, which occurs when the program calls free() on the same   
    memory pointer more than once.                                              
                                                                                
    Let’s walk through the program execution step by step to determine how      
    this happens.                                                               
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Step-by-step analysis:                                                      
                                                                                
    1. main() calls load_blob("abcdef")                                         
                                                                                
     • The string "abcdef" has length 6, which is greater than 4.               
     • This triggers the logic in load_blob at line 22:                         
                                                                                
        if (strlen(name) > 4) {                                                 
            free(b->name);      /* release the name on the recoverable error    
        path */                                                                 
            b->size = 0;                                                        
            return b;           /* hand the partially-initialised blob back     
        */                                                                      
        }                                                                       
                                                                                
     • So, the name buffer (allocated via strdup(name) at line 15) is freed     
       here.                                                                    
     • The function returns b, but b->name is now a dangling pointer (pointing  
       to already-freed memory).                                                
     • Crucially, b itself is not freed. So the blob_t struct is still          
       allocated and valid — only its name field has been freed.                
                                                                                
    2. Back in main():                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     blob_t *b = load_blob("abcdef");   /* triggers the recoverable error       
     path */                                                                    
     if (b && b->size == 0) {                                                   
         fprintf(stderr, "load_blob: empty blob, cleaning up\n");               
     }                                                                          
     destroy_blob(b);                                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     • b is non-null, and b->size == 0 (set in load_blob).                      
     • So the if block runs, printing: load_blob: empty blob, cleaning up.      
     • Then destroy_blob(b) is called.                                          
                                                                                
    3. Inside destroy_blob():                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_blob(blob_t *b) {                                      
         if (!b) return;                                                        
         free(b->name);          /* ← This is the problem */                    
         free(b);                                                               
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     • b is not null.                                                           
     • b->name was already freed in load_blob (line 23), so free(b->name) is    
       trying to free already-freed memory.                                     
     • This triggers the Deallocation of freed memory error (a                  
       heap-use-after-free or double-free).                                     
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Why is this happening?                                                      
                                                                                
     • load_blob frees b->name in the strlen > 4 path (a recoverable error).    
     • But it does not free b itself.                                           
     • Later, main calls destroy_blob, which calls free(b->name) again — but    
       the memory was already freed.                                            
     • This is the double-free.                                                 
                                                                                
    Even though destroy_blob is the function where free(b->name) is called,     
    the real root cause is that load_blob frees the name unnecessarily and      
    then leaves the responsibility to the caller — but the caller (via          
    destroy_blob) does not know the name was already freed.                     
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Key variables and their states:                                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
     Variable                Value                    Why                       
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────   
     b                       Non-null, allocated via  Created in load_blob,     
                             malloc(sizeof(*b))       returned unchanged        
     b->name                 Initially points to      Valid buffer              
                             strdup("abcdef")                                   
     b->name (after          Freed (in free(b->name)  Explicitly freed in       
     load_blob)              at line 23)              load_blob                 
     b->size                 0                        Set during load_blob      
                                                      after name was freed      
     b->name in              Dangling pointer         Already freed earlier     
     destroy_blob                                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Root Cause Summary:                                                         
                                                                                
    ▌ The load_blob function frees b->name on a recoverable error, but then     
    ▌ returns a pointer to a blob_t that still owns that memory. Later,         
    ▌ destroy_blob attempts to free b->name again, leading to a double-free.    
    ▌ The design flaw is that load_blob frees the name without informing the    
    ▌ caller, and the caller (a separate cleanup function) assumes the name     
    ▌ is still allocated.                                                       
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Fix 1: Minimal Local Fix (Quick workaround)                                 
                                                                                
    Change destroy_blob to avoid double-free:                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_blob(blob_t *b) {                                      
         if (!b) return;                                                        
         // Only free b->name if it’s not already freed                         
         if (b->name) {                                                         
             free(b->name);                                                     
             b->name = NULL;  // Prevent double-free                            
         }                                                                      
         free(b);                                                               
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This avoids the crash by checking if b->name is non-null before freeing     
    it. However, this is band-aid — it hides the underlying design issue.       
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Fix 2: Thorough Root-Cause Fix (Recommended)                                
                                                                                
    The issue lies in ownership and responsibility. Either:                     
                                                                                
     • load_blob should never free b->name, or                                  
     • The caller must be responsible for cleaning up.                          
                                                                                
    But load_blob is documented to "on a recoverable error, free the owned      
    name buffer and leave size at 0". So it claims ownership of the name, and   
    the caller should not free it later.                                        
                                                                                
    But then why is destroy_blob trying to free it again?                       
                                                                                
    → The real bug is that destroy_blob is being called on a blob returned by   
    load_blob even when the name was already freed.                             
                                                                                
    But in this code, destroy_blob should only be called on blobs that were     
    fully allocated. The blobs that return from load_blob with size == 0 are    
    partially initialized, and destroy_blob assumes name is still valid.        
                                                                                
    ✅ Correct Fix:                                                             
                                                                                
    Remove the call to free(b->name) from load_blob when returning b. Instead,  
    let the caller manage name, or ensure no double-free is possible.           
                                                                                
    However, if load_blob retains ownership of the name, and the caller later   
    invokes destroy_blob, then destroy_blob must be aware of the state.         
                                                                                
    But in this case, destroy_blob is expected to be the only place where b     
    and its fields are freed.                                                   
                                                                                
    So the proper fix is:                                                       
                                                                                
    ▌ Do not free b->name in load_blob if you are going to return b to be       
    ▌ destroyed later by destroy_blob.                                          
    ▌ Instead, if load_blob is to free name, it should also free the entire     
    ▌ b.                                                                        
                                                                                
    But it doesn’t — so it’s contradictory.                                     
                                                                                
    ✅ Final Recommendation: Fix load_blob to not free name if returning b      
                                                                                
    Change load_blob to not free b->name on error. Instead, let destroy_blob    
    be responsible, or ensure b is destroyed cleanly.                           
                                                                                
    Revised load_blob:                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static blob_t *load_blob(const char *name) {                               
         blob_t *b = (blob_t *)malloc(sizeof(*b));                              
         if (!b) return NULL;                                                   
         b->name = strdup(name);                                                
         b->size = 0;                                                           
         if (!b->name) {                                                        
             free(b);                                                           
             return NULL;                                                       
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         // Simulated recoverable parse error.                                  
         if (strlen(name) > 4) {                                                
             // Do NOT free b->name here.                                       
             // Just leave it as is, and let destroy_blob handle cleanup.       
             b->size = 0;  // Already zero                                      
             return b;    // Return unmodified blob                             
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         b->size = strlen(b->name);                                             
         return b;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Now:                                                                        
                                                                                
     • b->name is never explicitly freed in load_blob.                          
     • destroy_blob will safely free(b->name) and free(b) without risk.         
                                                                                
    You must not call free(b->name) inside load_blob and then return b to be    
    destroyed — that violates ownership.                                        
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
     1 Do not free b->name in load_blob when returning a partially initialized  
       blob_t that will be destroyed later.                                     
       The cleanup responsibility must be consistent. If destroy_blob is the    
       sole destructor, do not pre-emptively free b->name in load_blob.         
     2 Change load_blob to omit the free(b->name) line on error, as shown       
       above.                                                                   
     3 Remove any code path in load_blob that frees b->name but returns b,      
       because this leads to double-free when destroy_blob is called.           
                                                                                
    This resolves the root cause: preventing freeing memory twice by ensuring   
    b->name is freed only once — by destroy_blob, and only when b is valid and  
    not already cleaned up.                                                     
                                                                                
